Cell["\<\
But the important and interesting part is not comparison with SU(2) rotation \
angle, but with an actual classical knob (a parameter describing the loop in \
control space). Ramsey reads out SU(2) phase, and that phase depends on the \
loop knob with a half-angle rule. That half-angle is the SU(2) vs SO(3) \
difference. With that experimental scenraio in place, we shall see a \
vislization as below, which shows that the population is 4\[Pi]-periodic in \
the classical knob; That is the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]double cover\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] fingerprint in a one-qubit interferometric readout: \
period doubling in the control-loop parameter, not in the SU(2) angle.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.98059993455972*^9, 3.9806000373505163`*^9}, {
  3.9806001445606613`*^9, 
  3.9806001989578447`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9f4b03cf-0c43-4aab-be5d-\
d56a04ee1e06"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Plot", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "/", "2"}], "]"}], "^", "2"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{
