Cell[TextData[{
 "But how to implement above Ramsey scenario? How can a one-qubit Ramsey \
interference produce a 4\[Pi]-periodic signal in some classical loop knob, \
even though you can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t measure the global sign? The only way \
a single-qubit Ramsey experiment shows \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]4\[Pi] vs \
2\[Pi]\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] is if the measured Ramsey phase \[Gamma] \
depends on some classical loop knob ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "loop"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "432bff88-2bf2-426d-8a11-c3f8e7298469"],
 " as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Gamma]", "(", 
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "loop"], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "loop"], "/", "2"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"626b7433-9838-4ec0-92ed-2559925ffba6"],
 ", so that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["P", 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"]], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["sin", "2"], "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "loop"], "/", "4"}], ")"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"f868d316-3067-4d25-b14e-ccc2c94285f1"],
 " which is 4\[Pi] periodic in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "loop"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9660bea6-b8bd-4a70-ba04-224b6dd528df"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.98060020557516*^9, 3.980600220789466*^9}, {
  3.9806009112308064`*^9, 3.98060091301654*^9}, {3.980601010296463*^9, 
  3.980601100351289*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"05f64ee9-5ff1-441e-b6e6-\
1fcebb880578"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Consider a classical, programmable loop such that the effective field seen \
by the qubit ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "t", ")"}]}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"84ddfb22-5b31-4bcc-b6b1-a6950cd97c9a"],
 " moves around and returns to where it started: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "0", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "0", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "0", ")"}]}], "}"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "T", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "T", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "T", ")"}]}], "}"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"7f99a3cb-d69c-408f-a55d-7c777226e7f4"],
 ". The waveforms ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "t", ")"}]}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"5d95200c-a54f-4694-a110-465cad42c430"],
 " is what you literally upload into an Arbitrary Waveform Generator (AWG). \
AWG is one of the main classical instruments that creates the time-dependent \
control signals you use to drive and shape qubit pulses eg in a transmon + \
circuit QED step.  The AWG generates two baseband waveforms: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"I", 
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7f43908b-f1b3-442d-99b0-99d805f431b5"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"Q", 
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "445c99a7-72eb-4906-9acc-d6f51da7af8a"],
 ". An IQ mixer combines them with the LO to produce a shaped microwave tone. \
So the AWG is your ",
 StyleBox["classical knob",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " generator for: pulse amplitude ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"A", "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       RowBox[{"I", "(", "t", ")"}], "2"], "+", 
      SuperscriptBox[
       RowBox[{"Q", "(", "t", ")"}], "2"]}]]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"2237c3d7-d59a-4c4e-89fd-d8306416f4a1"],
 ", pulse phase ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[CurlyPhi]", "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"arctan2", "(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Q", "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"I", "(", "t", ")"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"00b3bb66-7087-43f4-8372-4e9f141ccb67"],
 ", pulse timing and shape. In the rotating frame, a driven transmon qubit is \
often modeled as: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "2"], 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "t", ")"}], ".", 
      OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "\[RightVector]"]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"28b192a0-74c5-48c5-ab3a-9fcd06f45836"],
 " where the AWG controls (through the IQ mixer): ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "t", ")"}], "\[Proportional]", 
    RowBox[{"I", "(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "677cefad-a0c3-470f-960a-becbb4ad5148"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "\[Proportional]", 
    RowBox[{"Q", "(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9515823a-f8e6-4ad6-9e7a-22a5ca05a8a3"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8ee937a5-f29d-4927-83be-3b42f5c0249d"],
 " is detuning (set by LO frequency choice and/or flux tuning). A classical \
loop of the control vector \[CapitalOmega](t) (AWG-programmed) is an \
SO(3)-type object (a 3-vector direction in ordinary space)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.980526087046165*^9, 3.980526233837812*^9}, {
   3.980526274797044*^9, 3.980526327271243*^9}, {3.9805264138964787`*^9, 
   3.9805264351571417`*^9}, {3.980526467692832*^9, 3.9805265704687967`*^9}, 
   3.9805266380837917`*^9, {3.980526737654285*^9, 3.980526765638981*^9}, {
   3.980526831789192*^9, 3.980526925327949*^9}, {3.980527130098324*^9, 
   3.98052719085306*^9}, 3.980527248126849*^9, {3.980527403630637*^9, 
   3.980527403631054*^9}, {3.9805371900790443`*^9, 
   3.980537190462289*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"af8d8d0f-ec08-44f9-ab86-\
a30944dc82e7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s rephrase above ideas again. You program the AWG to \
generate waveforms ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"I", 
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "12b93c26-99c2-4f8b-ad56-513938da7cd1"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"Q", 
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9add2cee-75e1-46fa-8568-142a52f3e72f"],
 ", and together with LO settings (and possibly flux tuning) you realize a \
time-dependent effective drive vector: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "t", ")"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "t", ")"}]}], "}"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"3c6953a4-da02-4067-84fd-04a86083ae51"],
 " . \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Closed loop\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] means ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "0", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "T", ")"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"8a012579-2add-4e59-9813-c94d64c01f99"],
 ". So at the beginning and end you have the same Hamiltonian. From the \
classical control perspective you did one full cycle and came back. A \
concrete AWG prescription is a constant magnitude \[CapitalOmega] where: \n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "x"], "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "sin", " ", "\[Theta]", " ", "cos", " ", 
     RowBox[{"\[Phi]", "(", "t", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e2db5792-fbe3-4690-940c-9ec1770579e6"],
 "\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "y"], "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "sin", " ", "\[Theta]", " ", "sin", " ", 
     RowBox[{"\[Phi]", "(", "t", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8513cdc8-0f92-4142-a963-b6a03cf4eddc"],
 "\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "z"], "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalOmega]", " ", "cos", " ", "\[Theta]", " "}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"e7b1fc00-8df1-4474-aa5c-dfb2caad61be"],
 "\nwith ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Phi]", "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]", " ", 
     RowBox[{"t", "/", "T"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "935d1dcd-766d-4c8d-8490-330371e8b8a1"],
 ".\n\nTherefore, the Hamiltonian becomes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"H", "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "2"], "\[CapitalOmega]", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       OverscriptBox["n", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "t", ")"}], ".", 
      OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "\[RightVector]"]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"da556699-333a-4a59-b35d-44bf32cbe864"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["n", "\[RightVector]"], "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sin", " ", "\[Theta]", " ", "cos", " ", 
       RowBox[{"\[Phi]", "(", "t", ")"}]}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"sin", " ", "\[Theta]", " ", "sin", " ", 
       RowBox[{"\[Phi]", "(", "t", ")"}]}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"cos", " ", "\[Theta]"}]}], "}"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"e729cec3-643b-48d6-9003-5963af8cddbe"],
 ". So the direction of the effective field traces a cone at fixed polar \
angle \[Theta], while the magnitude \[CapitalOmega] stays constant. This is \
the loop Hamiltonian (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"H", "(", "0", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"H", "(", "T", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7cb64d18-c90f-420d-af13-aa4e53aaa8a6"],
 ") that we will drive our qubit with. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9805273029121313`*^9, 3.980527439407755*^9}, {
  3.9805274925591497`*^9, 3.980527564540099*^9}, {3.980527595263804*^9, 
  3.980527643478664*^9}, {3.980527737168313*^9, 3.980527784886816*^9}, {
  3.980529935940304*^9, 3.980530070142043*^9}, {3.980538149008231*^9, 
  3.980538164081772*^9}, {3.9805385680724277`*^9, 
  3.980538610787978*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"299a4f23-6c81-48de-ba11-\
da78db06de4d"],

